{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_fireweed_ver01/data/sn84036287/00340581891/1937122401/1247.xml":{"full_text":"Carbon County News\ny 'If.-\n0. H. P. SHELLEY, Editor and Owner\nPublished every Friday at Red Lodge, Carbon Co.. Montana\nEntered at the Postoffice at Red Lodge, Montana, as Matter of\nSecond Class, under the Act of Congress of March 6, 1879.\nSubscription\u2014Per year. $2.50; six months, $1.50; three months,\n$.76. All subscriptions payable in advance.\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF CARBON COUNTY\nAND CITY OF RED LODGE\nTELEPHONE number nine\nTHE DILEMMA\nNow that the national debt is approaching the forty bil\nlion mark, and it seems vitally necessary that we have a\npolicy of retrenchment pointed toward balancing the bud\nget, the New Dealers at Washington are finding them\nselves between the two horns^of the dilemma. There is\ndanger that too much retrenchment may accelerate the\npresent business recession by continuing deflation, while\non the other hand there is the peril that continued pump\npriming may lead us into uncontrolled inflation and dis\naster.\nThe judgment of unbiased financial students at this\ntime is that there is no prospect of budget balancing in\nthe near future. Expenditures are increasing while feder\nal revenues are falling off. And the tendency is not now\nto impose new taxes in an effort to remedy the situation\nbut to repeal some of the taxes now in effect.\nIt looks likely therefore that for a few more months at\nleast the national debt will continue to increase and that\nwhile this may look necessary for tbe present? it will lead\nonly to trouble later on. As the Alexander Hamilton In\nstitute puts it; \"Business at the present time is being car\nried on at a greatly inflated level created to a considerable\nextent by government' borrowing during the past several\nyears. An elimination of government borrowing would\nremove one of the chief supports of this inflated structure.\nIts collapse would involve a more rapid fall in the national\nincome than in the price level, a consequent? curtailment\nof production with an increase in unemployment and a\ngeneral economic depression. T'\nWhile a balancing of the federal budget would not,\ntherefore, contribute to an immediate business revival but\nwould, on the contrary, accelerate the current recession,\na balancing of the budget would, in the long run, be worth\nmuch more than the price of a temporary slump. While\ngovernment borrowing would aid in checking the present\nrecession, it would mean a closer approach to the collapse\nof federal credit and such chaotic economic conditions\nthat even the 1929-1932 catasrophe would, in retrospect,\nseem like a mild recession.\nThe New Dealers seem to be getting into a position\nwhere it will be \"heck if you do and heck if you don't.\nThat will be a tough one to laugh off.\n\n\nOf course it's all right to get indignant and want to send some neigh\nbor's son to Asia to help the poor Chinese repel the Japs. But we won\nder, if the Japs were invading California, how many Chinese would\ncome over and help us?\nNow that the elections of November 1937 are over it is possible to\ntake the results and figure anything out of them about the future that\nyou care to.\n'll\n(Continued from Page 1/\na preliminary field survey of the\nYellowstone river for flood control,\nirrigation and power development\nwas half completed.\nPittsburgh\u2014Rivers rose through\nout Welitern Pennsylvannia and\nnorthern West Virginia threaten\ning inundations of low-areas.\nForeign\nMunich, Germany\u2014Gen. Erich\nLundendorff, considered the master\nmind of Germany's World War\narmies, died at the age of 72.\nLondon\u2014Three men lured a re\npresentative of a famous Bond\nstreet jewelry firm into a swank\nHyde Park hotel and robbed him\nof $80,009 worth of gems.\nShanghai\u2014Four times as many\nChinese planes crashed from poor\npiloting as Japanese guns shot\ndown. That tells the story of what\nhappened to China's air force.\nGeneva\u2014China's appeal against\nJapanese invasion of her territory\nwill be the outstanding question\nbefore the 100th session of the\nleague of nations council, called\nfor January 17.\nLondon\u2014Great Britian was re\nported building or planning 10 new\nbattleships to increase her number\nof capital ships to 25 in the new\nworld race for naval supremacy.\nRUES FOR MAH\nKROGNESS HELD\nPinal respects for Matthew\n'(Matt) Krogness, 62, prominent\nCarbon county farmer and stock\nman for the past 40 years, were\nheld from the Volney Creek church\nnear here at 3 p. m. Tuesday, the\nRev. A. B. Cornelson officiating.\nBurial was at Volney Creek ceme\ntery.\nPreceding the church rites, the\nBeartooth Lodge of Elks, of which\nKrogness was a member, held ser\nvices at the Elks home at I p, m.\nKrogness died of a heart attack\nThursday evening of last week,\nshortly after he aided in pushing\na truck that was stuck in some\nmud.\nBom in Norway on Feb. 21,\n1875, Krogness came to America\n46 years ago.\nSurvivors include the widow, a\nson, Carl, both at the home ranch;\na daughter, Agnes, a teacher at\nthe Cut Bank schools. There are\nalso three brothers and two sis\nters.\nThe Martin Funeral Home had\ncharge of arrangements.\nAt the Elks services the girls\nchoir of the Congregational\nchurch, under the direction of Mrs.\nR. A. Nutting, sang several hymns.\nFINNISH DRAMA\nHOLIDAY\nRed Lodge's Finnish Dramatic\nclub will present two plays during\nthe Christmas season, one op\nChristmas Day and one on New\nYear's Day.\nJohn Lampi is director of both\nproductions, which are sponsored\nby the Workers Building Associa\ntion and which will be held in\nWorkers' hall.\nAt 8:15 p, m. on Dec. 25, a cast\nof six will offer \"Onnen Veraja\"\n(The Gate of Luck), an agrarian\ntheme in three acts. Playing are\nArvo Larmi, Nelo Leeman, Tyyne\nNasi, Anna Huhtala, Toivo Nasi\nand Ahti Johnson.\nAt 7:45 p. m. on Jan. 1, a longer\nproduction, a Hungarian musical\ncomedy drama, will be staged. It\nis titled \"Vuoriston Poika\" (The\nMan of the MountanV.\nThe cast includes Toivo Nasi,\nKasper Nasi, John Lampi, Anna\nHuhtala, Ida Huovinen, Taimi\nNasi, John Hakala, Arvo Larmi\nand Ahti Johnson.\nBoth programs will be support\ned by the Red Lodge Boys' band,\nunder the direction of Sanfred Her\nlevi.\nA dance will be held after each\nof the plays.\nMiles City\u2014-J. H. Bohling, pres\nident of the Rocky Mountain as\nsociation of Fairs, announced the\nannual meeting of the organiza\ntion would be held in Billings Jan\nuary 24 and 25\nLegal Notice\nIN THE DISTRICT COURT OF\nTHE THIRTEENTH JUDICIAL DIS\nTRICT OF THE STATE OF MON\nTANA IN AND FOR THE COUNTY\nOF CARBON.\nTHE FEDERAL\nLAND BANK OF\nSPOKANE, a corpor\nation,\nPlaintiff,\n-vs\nIRWIN A. DRAPER,\na widower; Edwin W.\nDraper and\nDraper, husband and\nwife; Charles H. Dra\nper and Meryl Draper,\nhusband and wife;\nDraper Brothers, a co\npartnership; The Uni\nted\u00bb States National\nBank of Red Lodge,\nMontana, a corpora\ntion: and Red Lodge\nCreek National Farm\nIxian Association, a\ncorporation.\nDefendants,\nTO BE SOLD AT SHERIFF'S\nSALE, On tlie 28th day of December,\nA. D. 1937, at the hour of one O'clock,\np. m., of said day, at the front door\nof the Court House in the city of Red\nLodge, County of Carbon, State s of\nMontana, the following described real\nestate, situated in said County and\nState, to-wit:\nThe Southwest Quarter of the\nSoutheast Quarter of Section Thir\nty-three. Township Six South of\nRange Twenty, East of the Mon\ntana Meridian;\nLots Two and Three, the South\nHalf of the North Half, the East\nHalf of the Southwest Quarter and\nthe Southeast Quarter of Section\nFour; the Southeast Quarter of\nSection Five the Northwest Quar,\nter of the Northwest Quarter and\nthe'\" North\nQuarter of\nof Section Ten, Township Seven,\nof\nNOTICE\nAddle\nOP\nSHERIFF'S\nSALE\nHalf of the Southwest\nthe Northwest Quarter\nSouth of Range Twenty,\nthe Montana Meridian;\nAlgo the following described, tracts:\nBeginning at the Southeast Cor\nner of the Southwest Quarter of\nthe Northeast Quarter of Section\nFive. Township Seven South, of\nRange Twenty, East of the Mon\ntana Meridian, thence West 1125\nfeet, thence North 2\u00b0 23' West, 120\nfeet, thence North 46\u00b0 12' East,\n885 feet, thence South $4\" 47' East,\n470 feet, thence South 665 feet to\nthe point of beginning;\nThat certain tract of land situate\nin the Northeast Quarter of the\nNorthwest Quarter of Section\nNine, Township Seven South, of\nRange Twenty East, more partic\nularly described as follows: Be\nginning at a point Eight Hundred\nForty Feet We\u00e7t of the Quarter\nCorner oh the North side of Sec\ntion Nine, Township Seven South\nof Range Twenty East, thence\nSouth Seven Hundred Twenty-five\nfeet, thence West Ninety-six feet,\nthence South One Hundred Fifty\nfeet, thence West Forty feet, thence\nSouth Four Hundred Forty-five\nfeet, thence West Three Hundred\nForty-four feet to the Southwest\nCorner of said subdivision, thence\nNorth Thirteen Hundred! Twenty\nfeet, thence East Four Hundred\nEighty feet to the point of begin\nning, containing 12.8 acres, more\nor less; and\nThe Southeast Quarter of- the\nNortheast Quarter of Section Five,\nTownship Seven South, Range\nTwenty, East of the Montana Mer\nidian, excepting therefrom 14.46\nacres more particularly described\nas follows: Beginning at the North\nwest Comer of the Southeast Quar\nter of the Northeast Quarter of\nSection Five, Township Seven\nSouth of Range Twenty, East of\nthe Montana Meridian, thence East\n730 feet, thence South 5\u00b0 20' West\n470 feet, thence South 71\u00b0 22' East\n150 feet, thence North 34\u00b0 East\n435 feet, thence North 84\u00b0 22' Bast\n155 feet, thence South 31\u00b0 22' West\n280 feet, thence South,13\u00b0 15' West\n406 feet, thence North 84\u00b0 West 985\nfeet, thence North 675 feet to the\nplace of beginning.\nAlso, the following described water\nrtghts: 70 inches of the waters of\nRock Creek, decreed to Edward\nBurns, as of date June 23, 1894;\n265 inches of the ..waters of Rock\nCreek, decreed to Ada M. Draper\nas of date July 1, 1894, 41 inches\nof the waters of Ro.ck Creek, de\ncreed to Ada M. Draper as of date\nJune 15, 1895: 50 inches of the\nwaters of Rock Creek decreed to 1\nAda M. Draper*, as of date June\n1, 1902; and\nAll water and water rights used\nupon or appurtenant to said pro\nperty and however evidenced, in-\neluding (bu,t not limited to)\" a\nwater right evidenced by 150\nshares of stock In Pryde Ditch,\nComvany, evidenced by stock cer\ntificate number 22;\nTogether with all and singular\nthe tenements, hereditaments and\nappurtenances thereunto belonging\nor in anywise appert _\nDated at Red Lodge, Montana this\n30th day of November, A., ,\u00ef>\u00bb -1937.\nJ. R. McPATB\nSheriff.\npe\nCLAUDE A. JOHNSON\nRed Lodge, Montana\nAttorney for Plaintiff.\n(First Publication Dec. 3. 1937)\n(Fourth Publication Dec. 24, 1937)\nIN THE DISTRICT COURT OF\nTHE THIRTEENTH JUDICIAL DIS\nTRICT OF THE STATE OF MON\nTANA IN AND FOR THE COUNTY\nOF CARBON.\nR. A. NUTTING,\nPlaintiff,\nNOTICE\n-V8\nC. F. Chamberlain, as\nAdministrator of the\nestate of Alma War\nila, deceased; Mike\nMatson and Lula Mat\nson, husband and wife,\nDefendants, J\nTO BE SOLD AT SHERIFF'S\nSALE, On the 28th day of December,\nA. D. 1937, at the hour of one O'clock\np. m., of said day, at the front door\nof the Court House in the city of Red\nLodge, County of Carton, State of\nMontana, the following described real\nestate, situated in said County and\nState,\nLot numbered Four (4) in Block\nnumbered Fifty'-six (56) of the\nOriginal Plat of the city of Red\nLodge, Montana as the said lot\nand block are designated and de\nscribed oh the official plat thereof,\non file and of i'ecord in the office\nof the County Clerk and Recorder\nof Carbon County, at Red Lodge,\nOF\nSHERIFF'S\nSALE\nMontana.\nTogether with all buildings and\nImprovements thereon.\nTogether with all and singular the\ntenements, hereditaments and ap\npurtenances thereunto belonging\nor in anywise appertaining.\nDated at Red Lodge, Montana this\n30th day of November, A. D. 1937.\nJ. R. McFATE\nSheriff.\nCLAUDE A. JOHNSON\nRed Lodge, Montana\nAttorney for Plaintiff.\n(First Publication Dec. 3, 1937) _\n(Fourth Publication Dec. 24, 1937)\nnotice of sale\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN That\non Thursday, the 30th day of Decem\nber, 1937, a public auction will be held\nfor the sale of two astray horses de\nscribed as follows to-wit:\nOne (1) bay mare about twelve\n(12) years old, weight about 1200\npounds and bearing an unreadable\nbrand on the left shoulder; and\nalso\nOne (1) unbrandeff -brown filly\nabout two (2) \"years old.\nsaid sale to be held at the Caroline\nLockhart Ranch near the post office\nat Dryhead in Carbon County, Mon\ntana.\nNOTICE IS FURTHER GIVEN\nthat the owner or owners of said as\ntrays may claim the same on the date\naforesaid, and unless claimed said\nastrays will be sold at public auction\nto the highest bidder for cash.\nDated this 26th day of November,\n1937.\nJ. R. McFATE,\nSheriff of Carbon County and\nEx Officio Deputy State Stock\nInspector.\n(First Publication Dec. 3, 1937)\n(Fourth Publication Dec. 24, 1937)\nK\nCOURT OF\nTHE THIRTEENTH judicial dis\nTRICT OF THE STATE OF MON\nTANA IN AND FOR the COUNTY\nOF CARBON.\nr THE pedbral\nLAND B A N K O P\nSPOKANE, a corpor\nation.\nPlaintiff.\n-vs\nEdwin W. Draper and\nAddle Draper, hus\nband and wife: Irwin\nA. Draper, a widower:\nCharles H. Draper\n(also known as C. H.\nDraper) and Meryl\nDraper, husband and\nwife; The United\nstates National Bank\nof Red Lodge, Mon\ntana, a corporation;\nand 1 Red Lodge CTeek\nNational Farm Loan\nAssociation, a> Corpor\nation;\nNOTICE\nOP\nSHERIFF'S\nSALE\nDefendants, j\nTO BE SOLD AT SHERIFF'S\nSALE, On the 28th day of ^December,\nA. D. 1937, at the hour of one O'clock\np. m., of said day. at the front door\nof the Court House in the city of Red\nLodge, County of Carton, State of\nMontana, the following described real\nestate, situated in said County and\nState, to-wit:\n'The West Half of the Southwest\nS carter of Section Four. The West\nalf of the Southwest Quarter,\nthe South Half of the Southwest\nQuarter of the Northwest Quarter\nof Section Ten, all of Section, Nine,\nall in Township Seven, South or\nRange Twenty, East, excepting\ntherefrom that certain tract of lahd\nsituate in the Northeast Quarter\nof the Northwest Quarter of Sec-\ntion Nine, Township Seven, South\nof Range Twenty, East, more par-,\nticularly described as follows: Be\nginning at a point 840 feet West\nof the Quarter Corner on the North\nSide of Section Nine, said Town\nship and Rang\u00e9,\u00ab thfence South 725\nfeet, thence West 96 feet, thence\nSouth 150 feet, thence West 40\nfeet, thence South 445 feet, thence\nWest 344 feet to the Southwest\nCorner of said Subdivision thence\nNorth 1320 feet, thence East 480\nfeet to the point of beginning;\nAlso the following described\nwater rights; 70 inches of the wat\ners of Rock Creek decreed to Ed\nward Burns as. of date June 23,\n1894, 265 inches of the waters or\nRock Creek Xs decreed to Ada M-;*\"'\nDraper as\ninches of i\ndecreed to Ada M. Draper\nit date July 1, 1894, 41\ne waters of Rock Creek\nas of\ndate June 15th, 1895, and 50 inches\nof the waters of Rock Creek de\ncreed to Ada M. Draper as of date\nJune 1, 1902: and\nAll other water and water rights\nused upon or appurtenant to said\npremises\u00bb and however evidenced,\nincluding (but not limited to)\nwater rights evidenced by the fol\nlowing stock in the Pryde Ditch\nCompany, 233 shares certificate\nnumber 6, 232 shares certificate\nnumber 7 and 465 shares certificate\nnumber 23;.\nTogether with all and singular\nthe tenements, hereditaments and\nappurtenances thereunto belonging\nor In anywise appertaining;\nDated at Red Lodge, Montana this\n30th day of November, A. D. 1937.\nJ. R. McFATE\nSheriff.\nCLAUDE A. 'JOHNSON\nRed Lodge, Montana\nAttorney for Plaintiff.\n(First Publication Dec. 3, 1937)\n(Fourth Publication Dec. 24, 1937)\nIN THE DISTRICT COURT OF THE\nTHIRTEENTH JUDICIAL DISTRICT\nOF THE STATE OF MONTANA, IN\nAND FOR THE COUNTIES OF YEL\nLOWSTONE, BIG HORN, CARBON,\nSTILLWATER AND TREASURE.\nIn the Matter, of TERMS!\nOF COURT for the year\n1938, in the Five \u00c7toun-V\nties Comprising, the Thir\nteenth Judicial District 1\nof the State of Montana.)\nXT IS HS\u00d6\nthe terms of\nThirteenth Judicial District of the\nState of Montana, for the year 1938,\nshall convene 8 and open in the Coun\nties composing said Judicial District,\noil the following dSates:\nYELLOWSTONE COUNTY:\u2014\nJanuary 31,\nApril 18,\nJuly 18,\nOctober 24.\nBIG HORN COUNTY;\u2014January 20,\nApril 14,\nJuly 14.\nOctober 6.\nCARBON COUNTY:\u2014 January 21\nApril 15,\nJuly 15,\nORDER\nORDERED, That\nifrict' Court of the\nI Dis\nOctober 7.\nSTILLWATER COUNTY:\u2014\nJanuary 19,\nApril 20,\nJuly 20,\nOctober 19.\nCOUNTY :\u2014January\nApril 26,\nJuly 26,\nOctober 25.\nIT IS FURTHER ORDERED. That\nail matters of NATURALIZATION\nshall be called for consideration in the\ndifferent Counties, as follows:\nYellowstone County,\u2014April 2nd and\nSeptember 23rd.\nBig Horn County.\u2014April 7th and\nSeptember 22nd.\nCarbon County,\u2014April 4th and Sep\ntember 24th.\nStillwater County,\u2014April 20th and\nSeptember 21st.\nTreasure County,\u2014April 26th and\nSeptember 27th.\nIT IS FURTHER ORDERED, That\nthe LAW and MOTION DATS shall\nbe as follows 8\u2014\nYellowstone County,\u2014Every Judicial\nday of the month except Satur\nday.\nBig Horn County,\u2014Every Thursday.\nCarbon County,\u2014 Every Friday.\nStillwater 1 County, \u2014Third Wednes\nday of each Month.\nTreasure County,\u2014 Fourth Tuesday\nof each month.\nDated this 1st day of December, A.\nD\u201e 1937.\n25,\nTREASURE\nGUY C. DERRY,\nDistrict Judge.\nBEN HARWOOD,\nDistrict Judge.\n(First Pub. Dec. 10, 1937)\n(Third Pub. Deo. 24, 1937)\nIN THE DISTRICT COURT OF THE\nTHIRTEENTH JUDICIAL DIS\nTRICT OF THE STATE OF MON\nTANA, IN AND FOR THE COUN\nTY OF CARBON.\nIn the Matter of! NOTICE OF AD*\nthe Estate of .MJ NJ\u00aeTJJIATR|X* S\nLouis Tervo, -SALE OF REAL\nDeceased. ESTATE AT PRI\nJ VATE SALE.\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN, That\nin pursuance of ah Order of the Dis\ntrict Court of the Thirteenth Judic\nial District of the State of Montana,\nin and for the County of Carbon made\non the 14 th day of December, 1937,\nin the matter of the estate of Louis\nTervo, deceased, the undersigned, the\nadministratrix of the estate of said\ndeceased, will sell at private sale in\none parcel to the highest bidder upon\nthe terms and conditions hereinafter\nmentioned and subject to confirma\ntion by said! court on or after the\n11th day of January, 1938. all right,\ntitle, interest and estate of the said\nLouis Tervo, deceased, at the time of\nhis death in and to the real property\nhereinafter described and all right,\ntitle and interest that the said estate\nhas by operation of law or otherwise\nacquired other than or in addition to\nthat of said deceased at the lime of\nhis death of, in and to those certain\nlots, pieces or parcels of land situate,\nlying and being in .the\u00bb City of Red\nLodge, County of Carbon, State of\nMontana, and more particularly de\nscribed as follows, to-wit:\nThe North Sixteen feet and Three\ninches of Lot numbered Fifteen,\nand the South Twelve feet and\nSix inches of Lot numbered Six\nteen, in Block numbered Fourof\nthe Original Plat of the Glty\nof Red Lodgs, Montana, as\nsaid Lot and Block-art designat\ned and described on the Official\nPlat thereof on file und! of record\nin the office of the County Clerk\nand Recorder of Carbon County at\nRed Lodge, Montana, excepting\nand expressly reserving from the\nabove described premises, all coal,\nores and minerals, and all mineral\nrights in. to and upon the afore\nsaid premises, and every part\nthereof, -excepting the surface\nthereof.\nTERMS AND CONDITIONS OF\nSALE; Cash In lawful money of the\nUnited States of America, ten per\ncent of the purchase money to bo\npaid at the time of sale and balance\non confirmation of sale, abstract of\ntitle at expense of purchaser, and the\npurchaser to assume the payment of\nand take the property subject to all\nstate and county taxes and all as\nsessments Of whatsoever name and\nnature .which are now or may be\ncome hereafter chargeable to or a\nlien against the property purchased\nby him. All bids or offers must be In\nwriting and may be left at the home\nof said Administratrix at Red Lodge,\nMontana, or may be left at the law\noffices of H. A. Simmons and Hubert\nA. Simmons, Jr\u201e Attbrneys for said\nAdministratrix, at Red Lodger Mon\ntana. or may be filed in the office of\nthe Clerk of said Court at Red Lodge,\nMontana, at any time after the first\npublication of this notice, and'before\nthe making of the sale.\n^Dated this 15th day of December,\nALINA TERVO,\nAdministratrix of the Estate of\nLouis Tervo, Deceased.\nH. A. Simmons and\nHubert A. Simmons, Jr.\nBy H. A. Simmons,\nAttorneys for Administratrix.\n(First Publication Dec. 17. 1937)\n(Fourth Publication Jan. 7*. 1938.)\nM\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS\nESTATE OP JAMES P. HATTEN,\nNOTICE'IS HEREBY GIVEN By\nthe undersigned, Administratrix of\nthe estate of James P. Hatten, de\nceased, to the creditors of, and all\npersons having claims against the\nsaid deceased, to exhibit them, with\nthe necessary vouchers, within Ten\nmonths after the. first publication of\nthis notice, to the said administratrix\nat the law office of E. P. Conwell,\nUnited States National Bank Bull'd\ning. Red Lodge, Montana, the same\nbeing the place for the transaction\nof the business of said estate in the\nCounty of Carbon.\nDated December 17, 1937.\nEDITH HATTEN,\nAdministratrix of the estate of\nJames F. Hatten, Deceased.\n(First Publication Dec. 24,- 1937)\n(Fourth Publication Jan. 14, 1937)\nNOTICE OF ANNUAL MEETING\nNotice is hereby given that the an\nnual meeting of the stockholders of\nthe Red Lodge Improvement Com\nwiil be held at the United States\nBank of Red Lodge. Mon\non Tuesday, January 4, 1938,\nM WlI\nmal\ntana,\nat 7:30 o'clock P. M.\nThe meeting is held for the purpose\nof e\nlecting three directors to serve\nthe ensuing year and for the\ntransaction of any other business\n.that may lawfully come before the\nmeeting.\nAll proxies must be in writing and\nfiled with the secretary.\nDated December 24, 1937.\nCHARLOTTE DILWORTH,\n(First Publication Dec. 24, 1937)\n(2nd! Publication Dec. 31, 1937)\nfor\nPOTATOES REMOVED\nTO OTHER COUNTIES\nThe quota of three carloads of\npotatoes which were to have been\npurchased from the surplus in\nCarbon County, has been removed\nand distributed to other counties,\nsince apparently the farmers were\nnot interested in the price offered\nby the government for the federal\npurchase of potatoes for relief and\ntheir requirement, calling for 80%\ngrade No, 1%, and the use of new\nsacks, at the purchase price of 60c\nwas discouraging to most of them,\nstated the County Agent; Since\nonly two farmers agreed to the\nsale, and the combined lot of these\nwere not equal to a carload, a\ntelephonic message from Mr. Spar\nling, State Commissioner of Agri\nculture, stated that the quota was\nbeing given to other counties.\n_ _\nFri. Sat., Dec. 24^26. RAINBOW\nNITE SATURDAY! CHRISTMAS\nSPECIAL ERROL FLYNN,\nJOAN BLONDELL, EDW. EVER\nETT HORTON in \"THE PER\nFECT SPECIMEN\". Even a Per\nfect man can learn plenty from a\nnot-so-perfect 'blonde! Perfect En\ntertainment! Added: \"THE\nPAINTED STALLION\" No. 2\nFox News! Shows 7 9. PAL\nNITE FRIDAY! Matinee Xmas\nDay, 2 p. m.\nSun. Mon. Tues., Dec. 26-27-28.\nBETTE DAVIS, OLIVIA De Havil\nland, Leslie Howard in \"IT'S\nLOVE I'M AFTER\". Three hearts\nthat beat as one! If it's Love\nyou're after, yoij'd better get af\nter your man! Added: Vaudeville\nReel, Betty Boop Cartoon, News!\nNew Year Special! Fri. Sat.,\nDec. 31-Jan. 1. RAINBOW NITE\nSATURDAY! Tyrone Power and\nLoretta Young, in their perfect\npicture together! \"SECOND HON\nELMOON\". Love at first sight was\nromantic enough, but love at sec\nond sight m-m-m! Added: \"THE\nPAINTED STALLION\" No. 3,\nColor Cartoon, News! Shows 7\n9! Matinee 2 P. M. New Year's\nDay!\nComing! Sun. Mon, Tues., Jan.\n2-3-4. First South Seas Adventure\nRomance ever filmed in TECHNI\nCOLOR! OSCAR HOMOLKA,\nFRANCES FARMER, RAY MIL\nLAND in \"EBB TIDE\". Robert\nLouis Steven's drama of a mad\nman's folly, of a woman's courage\nwhich raises three pieces of hu\nman driftwood to the Height of\nHeroes!\nINSTALLATION OF\n(Continued from Page 1)\nconductress; Mrs, Mary Robison,\nchaplain; Mrs. Elva Downs, mar\nshall; Mrs. Mayme Bowman, war\nder; Mrs. Maude Horton, sentinel,\nand the following Star Point of\nficers: Mrs. Margaret Newman,\nMrs. Ina Beadle, Mrs. Marietta\nNorton, Mrs. Hilma Akers and\nMrs. Alice Graves.\nMrs. Georgia Schwin has been\nnamed instructor.\na\nROBERTS\nBy Mrs. A. E. Halkklla\nMrs. Rose Wlekierack, Mr. and\nMrs. H. G. Weir and Mr, and Mrs.\nT. F. Schrumpf and son, Elvin,\nwere guests at the home of Mrs,\nHedwig Platt last Saturday eve\nning, the occasion being Mrs.\nPlatt's birthday.\nMr. and Mrs. Albert Budas and\ngrandson, Richard, left Saturday\nevening for Long Beach, Califor\nnia to spend the holidays.\nMrs. Fred Hill was hostess last\nWednesday afternoon Whjen she\nentertained her card club at her\nhome here.\nMrs. George Hunt and her\ndaughter, Miss Edith, were dinner\nguests at the H. G. Weir home\nlast Wednesday evening.\nMr. and Mrs. Ernest Luoma and\nson of Butte and Mr. \"Sonnie\nStein of Rock Springs, Wyoming,\nare here for the holidays at the\nhome of their parents, Mr. and\nMrs. Emil Stein.\nMiss Myrtle Stockfisch was a\nweek-end guest at the J. T.\nFlahertty home in Red Lodge.\nMiss Genevieve Wilmonen ar\nrived) Saturday from Oak Creek,\nColorado to spend the Christmas\nholidays with her parents, Mr. and\nMrs. Andrew Wilmonen.\nMr. Raymond Allen left Tuesday\nfor Portland, Oregon, for a visit\nwith his sisters, Mae, Josie and\nMrs. Fred Butcher,\nMr. and Mrs. Sieve Bosso have\narrived from Butte to take up their\nhome in Roberts for the winter.\nP ARK THEATRE\nWEEKLY PROGRAM\nCHRISTMAS SPECIAL!!! SAT.\nSUN. MON. TUES, Dec. 25-26\n27-28. 4 GIGANTIC DAYS. JEAN\nETTE MacDONALD in \"THE\nFIREFLY\" with Allan Jones\nWarren William. THE GREATEST\nMUSICAL DRAMA YET PRO\nDUCED! More adventurous than\nMaytime\"! More thrilling than\nNaughty Marietta\"! More melod\nious than \"Rose Marie\"! MATIN\nEE CHRISTMAS DAY AT 2 P. M.\nMATINEE SUNDAY AT 2 P. M.\nEVENING SHOWS AT 6:30\n9:10!!\nWed. Thurs., Dec. 29-30. DOUB\nLE FEATURE. No. 1. JOHN\nWAYNE, Sheila Bromley in \"IDOL\nOP THE CROWDS\". He was a\nspeed marvel in the world's fas\ntest game\u2014hockey! No. 2. JOHN\nNY MACK BROWN, WALLACE\nBEERY in \u00abBILLY THE KID\",\nThrilling true life drama of the\nsouthwest's \"Kid\" bandit killer!\nDon't miss this! RAINBOW NITE\nWEDNESDAY.\nPri. Sat., Dec. Sl-Jan. 1st.\nNEW YEAR'S SPECIAL. The\nPour Horsemen of Hilarity bring\ning you the love-life of a padded\ncell! Bert Lahr\u2014Jimmy Savo\u2014Bil\nly House Mischa Auer\u2014Joy\nHodges\u2014'Alice Brady in \"MERRY\nGO-ROUND of 1938\" A ten. star\nfun frolic that will start the New\nYear right for you! Also short\nsubjects! Matinee New Year's Day\n2 p. m.\nU\n\nCHURCH NOTES\nFIRST ENGLISH LUTHERAN\nCHURCH\nA. B. Cor nelson, Paator\nService in the Assembly room of\nthe public library Sunday evening,\nJan 2, at 7:30.\nChristmas service at Joliet Sun\nday morning, Dec. 26th, at 11:00.\nSunday school program, practice in\nthe afternoon. -Christmas tree pro\ngram in the evening at 7:30. The\nLadies Aid will hold a New Year's\nParty Friday evening, Dec. 31st.\nThe place will be announced later.\nMETHODIST EPISCOPAL\nCHURCH\nRev. Charles Rhodes, Pastoi\nThe Sunday School will meet at\n9:45 a. m. The class offerings will\nbe for Missions.\nAt 11 o'clock, the entire Sunday\nSchool, along with the other de\npartments of the Church, will take\npart in a beautiful service \"White\nGifts for the King.\" Each class,\nwith appropriate exercises will pre\nsent its offering in a white enve\nlope, placing it in the Manger\nCradle which will be at the center\nof the service. Not only offerings\nof Substance are desired, but the\ngiving of Self, and of Service.\nPledges may be written, and hand\ned in along with contributions for\neither Missions or the Local\nChurch, and the same will be col\nlected and placed in the Cradle as\n\"White Gifts for the King.\" Any\ndesiring to \"Join the Church\" or\nreceive the Sacrament of Baptism,\nwill be welcomed. It is hoped that\nparents and friends will be pre\nsent at this service.\nOn Wednesday, Dec. 29th., the\nEpworth League will arrange for\nPictures and a Play in the Church.\nLantern slides on Africa will be\nshown, together with an illustrat\ned hymn \"We've a Story to tell to\nthe Nations.\" The Roberts Young\npeople will give a Play \"Why the\nChimes Rang.\" The meeting will\ncommence at 7:30, and there will\nbe a silver offering taken for the\nEpworth League.\n\u25a0\u00f6\nSJ\nmSSmmm\u00e2m\n:I\n\nMM\nWALLUM'S\nSOLEMN\nBy EVERETT WALLUM\nMER' CHRISHMUS!\n\"Ah here we are in Red Lodge,'\u00bb\njolly old rosy-cheeked Santa Mc\nClaus shouted as he neared the\ncity. \"Ah there's the people wait\ning for me now. Nope I guess\nthat's a crowd entering a beer par\nlor. Oh, there's the good kiddies\nover there. Whoa Dancer (high\nschool cutie stops doing the Big\nJonathan), whoa Prancer (little\nboy with ants in pants continues\nprance)'' Donnie, Blixie also stop,\nthe little deers.\n\"Now.kiddies, I know there's an\nordinance against peddling here,\nbut everybody else's doing it and\nwhy not good old Santy? Now\nI'll take my bag here (to wife,\nwho was under seat \"no I didn't\nmean you honey\") and give all the\ngood boysies and girlies their pre\nsents.\nyy\nI\nStep up, Joe Yelich. Here's a\nthimble and two short breaths.\nNow you can also sew a pair of\npants for your bowling team.\n99\nAND SPEAKING OP BOWL\nING. I HAVE SOMETHING\nSPECIALLY NICE FOR YOU,\nBETTY KEMP. HERE IS A POP\nCORN BOWLING BALL FOR\nYOU TO USE. NOW YOU WON'T\nMAKE SO MANY STRIKES!\n\n\"Ah, Coach' Hartwig. Here's just\nthe thing, and aren't you glad you\ndidn't make that face at the ref\neree the other night! It's an ear\ntrumpet. Yes sir! Now when any\nof the fickle fans start pouring it\non in case your cagers should lose\na game all you've got to do is use\nthis and yell 'hey?' They'll think\nyou're deaf and drop the whole\nmatter.\n99\n\n\"And who's this shrinking little\nbuttercup? If it isn't Emil Dimich.\nNo longer will they laugh when\nyou get up to speak\u2014though\nyou'd better be sure to wear your\ntrousers. Here's a special course,\nwith pictures, on making talks in\npublic. Remember you can't use it\nafter curfew hours!\n\n\"Step up D. W. Columbus. A\nreal surprise for you, you manly\nlittle fellow. Here's a feather b\u00e9d\nso's you can be happy, even while\ndreaming. What did you say? Oh\nyou said it's a lot of bunk. Ho, ho,\nho.\"\nAnd for Mike Hudak, I've just\nthe thing for these cold winter\nmornings. A jumping jack! Now\nyou won't have to chase the streets\nscaring up those cute little rab\nbits. Just press the little button\nlike this, see, and, Ouch! take the\ndratted thing!\n\"And to Gail Nelson, the best\nboy here, I'm giving a singing top.\nIf your head spins, it sings, does\nn't it Well, go do a highland fling.\nHa, ha, even ;Santa has his jokes.\nBut, just to give you added pleas\nure, here's a set of blocks so you\ncan Block that Pun about you in\nWallum's Solemn Column.\"\nAnd as for you, Mr. .Wallum,\nhow did you get here? Well, you'\nre here, so here's a handful of\nmoss so you won't gather any\nstones rolling towards your cran\nium. As far as I'm concerned you\ncan eat the moss!\"\n\nFor Leo Spogen we have a\nspecial set of inflation scales, on\nwhich he can weigh the fish he\ncatches. On these scales, a two\npound fish will weigh at least five\npounds. Another thing. The scales\nwork, even with fish caught in the\nhigh C\"s.\nI\nTO MARGE CRUTCHER WE\nGIVE WATER ON THE KNEE,\nSO THAT ANY TIME IT COMES\nTO A BOIL SHE CAN KICK IT\nAROUND.\"\n\"To George Throop, we give a\npacket of Mink seeds so he can\nexpand his mink farm. When he\ngets mink enough for about a\nthousand fur coats, then him'n me\nwill step around a bit with the\nfemmes, (to wife\u2014-Ouch).\n\"Here's a disgruntled husband\nhere. My! This will never do. He's\nalways said he'd like to get his\nhands on something sweet, so\nhere's a candy cane\n\"And to his wife here we pre\nsent a boa constrictor. She always\nsaid she'd like to get her hands\non that worm.\"\n\nAnd, as Santa asks if every\nbody's happy, the mob surges for\nward, singing, \"Santa McClaus is\nleaving this town.\n99\nHO, HO, HO HUM PERIOD.\nI\nButte\u2014Coroner M. P, Duff an\nnounced that investigation into the\ndeath of an unindentified\nwhose body was found near Mel\nrose had been dropped due to lack\nof tangible clues.\nman","height":"21735","width":"16410"}}
